# Wayfarer Build Guardrails

These rules exist so a change to one feature cannot silently break another.
Every item below is a **HARD RULE** unless it explicitly says otherwise.

---

## 1. Data Classification — T1 / T2 / T3

Every table, column, and log field is one of:

- **T1 — Restricted personal / safety data.** PII, auth identifiers,
  geolocation, health/medical, travel-document numbers, financial
  instruments, minor data, evidence files. **Encrypt at rest (SSE-KMS with
  per-user DEK for storage), never log raw, never return to unauthenticated
  clients, never embed in analytics payloads, 15-minute presigned URLs only.**
- **T2 — Personal operational data.** Trip names, destinations, itinerary
  fragments, coverage conclusions, non-identifying preferences. Encrypted in
  transit, RLS-gated by ownership/membership, may be cached server-side but
  never in third-party analytics.
- **T3 — Platform metadata.** Feature registry, event type registry, severity
  classes, public marketing content. Readable by `authenticated` broadly;
  writable only by maintainers via migration or SECURITY DEFINER RPC.

Every new column declares its class in the migration summary header.

## 2. Row-Level Security — Non-Negotiable

- Every new table: `ALTER TABLE … ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;` in the same
  migration that creates it. No exceptions.
- Never `USING (true)`. Never `FOR ALL`. Always four separate policies
  (SELECT / INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE) with explicit ownership or membership
  checks.
- `auth.uid()` only — never `current_user`.
- SELECT: USING only. INSERT: WITH CHECK only. UPDATE: USING + WITH CHECK.
  DELETE: USING only.
- When a table references another table for authorization, the policy uses
  `EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM …)` against `auth.uid()`; it never trusts a column
  on the row being inserted as the authorization source.

## 3. Event Ledger Immutability

- `event_ledger` is **append-only**. Never `UPDATE` or `DELETE` rows.
- Metadata tables (`event_type_registry`, `feature_registry`) are not the
  ledger; they can be corrected via migration, but every correction emits an
  `event_type_registry_correction` or equivalent governance event to the
  ledger with before/after state.
- Never emit ledger events from client code. All emissions go through
  SECURITY DEFINER RPCs that validate the caller's scope.

## 4. Migrations — Never Modify History

- **Never edit an applied migration file.** Forward-only corrections via a
  new migration.
- Every migration starts with the multi-line block-comment summary described
  in the root Supabase doctrine.
- Every DDL is guarded: `IF NOT EXISTS` / `IF EXISTS` / `DO $$ … END $$`
  conditionals for columns that may already exist.
- Never issue `DROP TABLE`, `DROP COLUMN`, `TRUNCATE`, or `DELETE` without an
  accompanying ADR explaining the data-loss path and a preservation strategy.
- Never issue bare `BEGIN`/`COMMIT`/`ROLLBACK`. (PL/pgSQL `DO $$ BEGIN … END $$`
  blocks are fine.)

## 5. feature_registry INSERT Rule

- Every new user-facing feature inserts one `feature_registry` row in the
  migration that delivers it, with: `feature_id`, `display_name`,
  `description`, `default_enabled` (false unless doctrine says otherwise),
  `minimum_mode`, `phase`, `capability_tier_current`, `capability_tier_max`,
  `requires_connector`, `connector_status`, and (if a sub-feature)
  `parent_feature_id`.
- Every event type inserted into `event_type_registry` declares its
  `feature_id`. Referencing a feature that does not exist is a migration-time
  error.
- Feature IDs are immutable. If a feature is renamed or retired, add a new
  row and deprecate the old one — do not reassign the ID.

## 6. Cross-Feature Non-Breakage (Dependency Discipline)

- Before modifying any shared table (`incidents`, `trips`, `event_ledger`,
  `event_type_registry`, `feature_registry`, `claims`, `coverage_graph`,
  `evidence`, `policies`, `policy_versions`), list every feature that reads
  or writes it (§9a dependency declaration) at the top of the PR / migration
  comment. If the list is not obvious, `rg` for the table name across
  `supabase/migrations/`, `app/`, and `lib/` first.
- Additive-only changes to shared tables (new nullable columns, new indexes,
  new policies). Any breaking change (type narrowing, NOT NULL on existing
  column, rename) requires an ADR + two-phase migration (expand → backfill →
  contract).
- New RPCs never change the signature of an existing RPC. If behavior must
  change, deprecate the old name and introduce a new name; leave the old one
  until its last caller is gone.

## 7. SECURITY DEFINER & search_path

- Every SECURITY DEFINER function sets `SET search_path = ''` (or an
  explicit, minimal schema list) as a function attribute.
- SECURITY DEFINER functions validate `auth.uid()` explicitly; they never
  assume the caller is authorized just because the function was invoked.
- SECURITY DEFINER is the only mechanism for writing to T3 metadata tables
  from user-facing RPCs.

## 8. Edge Functions

- Supabase Edge Functions only. No other serverless providers.
- Never share code between functions via relative imports; each function is
  a standalone deployable.
- CORS headers are the exact set: `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`;
  `Access-Control-Allow-Methods`: must include OPTIONS and every method the
  function accepts; `Access-Control-Allow-Headers: Content-Type,
  Authorization, X-Client-Info, Apikey`. Applied to every response including
  errors.
- Entire handler wrapped in try/catch.
- `npm:` or `jsr:` specifiers only; never `deno.land/x`, `esm.sh`, or `unpkg`.

## 9. Client-Side Hooks

- Any file that uses `useState`, `useEffect`, `useRouter`, `useContext`, etc.
  starts with `"use client"`. No exceptions.
- `supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange` callbacks are **never declared `async`**.
  Wrap async work inside an IIFE inside the sync callback to avoid deadlocks.

## 10. Never-Purple Rule & UX

- No purple, indigo, or violet hues anywhere unless the product owner
  requests them explicitly.
- All text maintains ≥ 4.5:1 contrast on every background state, including
  transition states (transparent → solid header backgrounds).
- 8px spacing system; 3 font weights maximum; 150% body line-height, 120%
  heading line-height.

## 11. Secret Handling

- No secret values in repo. `.env` is dev-local only.
- Deployed secrets are managed via `mcp__supabase__list_edge_function_secrets`
  and the Supabase dashboard. Reference secret existence by name, never
  assume a value.
- Never hard-code a Supabase anon key, service key, or third-party key in
  committed code.

## 12. MISMATCH_LOG Discipline

- Any detected drift between repo and DB — no matter how small — gets an
  entry in `lib/MISMATCH_LOG.md` before any remediation code is written.
- An entry is closed (RESOLVED) only when both repo and DB agree and a
  verification query has been run.

---

## Enforcement

A change that violates one of these rules is blocked at review. A change
that requires a temporary exception must cite the rule number in the PR
description and include an ADR in `docs/adr/` justifying the exception and
its sunset date.
